SIMPLE: govern
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Govern
<hw>Gov"ern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Governed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Governing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>governer</ets>, F. <ets>gouverner</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>gubernare</ets> to steer, pilot, govern, Gr. <grk>kyberna^n</grk>.
Cf. <er>Gubernatorial</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To direct and
control, as the actions or conduct of men, either by established laws or
by arbitrary will; to regulate by authority.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Fit to
<xex>govern</xex> and rule multitudes.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To regulate; to influence; to direct; to restrain;
to manage; <as>as, to <ex>govern</ex> the life; to <ex>govern</ex> a
horse.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Govern</qex> well thy appetite.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>To require to be in a particular
case; <as>as, a transitive verb <ex>governs</ex> a noun in the objective
case</as>; or to require (a particular case); <as>as, a transitive verb
<ex>governs</ex> the objective case</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Govern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Govern
<hw>Gov"ern</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To exercise authority; to
administer the laws; to have the control.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Governability</ent>⟦br⟧
